column12: Measurement condition : Ice; Clear , No Precipitation , Calm Wind Swirling/Variable
column13: CIC
column14: Frozen to bottom downstream of gauge. Over ice flow from upstream. Drilling hole at gauge caused large and continual gyser of water and over ice flow with mixed with the existing over ice flow. Unable to measure under ice flow due to gyser from holes. Measured over ice flow at the control. FT2 measurement, SNR errors due to clarity of water. Velocity angled, boundary interference, and spikes throughout due to shallow measurement depth and water clarity. Section of channel where ice was heaved, no flow over ice, drilled hole in this area, could not locate water under ice in this section.   Likely 0 flow under ice prior to arrival, drilling in to the gauge pool released the hydraulic pressure under ice causing the gyser. EST shift to bring discharge to 0 should be applied back to March 1. Measurement shift can be used as a single point of reference for this visit. @ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @ HG (well) frozen, use HG2 record for stage. Thick ice in gauge pool with significant over ice flow and ponded water. Hole drilled for DWL at 14:05 caused water to drain in to hole. SRC of -0.365 found to OTT sensor, did not reset. Shot second DWL to confirm reset, drilled new hole as existing DWL hole in ice was filling with over ice flow and possibly not connected, possibly in ponded layer. Ice was too deep for auger, broke through ice with ice bar and gyser of aerated water shot out. Gyser roughly 30 cm in height, causing large over ice flow. Pictures attached. Gyser would not slow down, large amount of blocked water releasing through hole. Drilling downstream was frozen to bottom. Drilling holes on either side of gyser were too deep with ice to chip with ice bar. Took DWL from hole with gyser at 15:00 and found similar water level to prior DWL, SRC to OTT at 15:00 was 0.255m. Water level in logger between 14:45 and 15:00 dropping rapidly due to gyser and water exiting gauge pool. Did not reset logger again due to rapidly changing water level, multiple estimated SRCs will likely be required pre and post visit. Shot 3rd water level after measurement to confirm. Water level is slowly dropping under ice. Although all DWLs are within the tolerance of the observed surge. SRC to OTT 0.330m, not reset. Assumed that force of water exiting gauge pool is causing fluctuations in stage / OTT movements. Will return to station at end of week to obtain another DWL and reset. Pre and post hole drilling the ehad stage over the HG2 sensor dropped roughly 0.500m, so the stage recorded by the OTT may be valid, and the water level taken at the gyser is not representative. after 14:40. Mid-section
